title: For Sale/Trade:  M38 Mosin for sale or trade for M1891 Mosin or WWI SMLE/ShtLE
postcontent:
The M38 is a 1944 Izhevsk produced M38 rifle. The bluing is great, and the rifle was degreased by a previous owner, who probably only shot it a few times. Bore is shiny with strong rifling. The receiver is smooth, not the typical rough finish of the wartime expedient rifles. Shellac is in good shape with only a few handling marks. Deep red shellac typical of the post war refurb, and an M44 stock. Bolt does not match the receiver, another typical refurb feature. Normally Ivan the factory worker would grind down the old serial and engrave the new one, guess he was feeling lazy when he got to this rifle. Comes with a sling. Overall, a very nice example of an M38 rifle.

Would like to trade for an M1891 rifle, the one that came before the 91/30. I might also consider a nice WWI Lee-Enfield rifle from 1918 or before. Maybe even a Berthier or Lebel from 1918 or before. No sporters please. I would prefer that the M1891 is complete and at least has the upper handguard. O wil sell for $340 I am located in NE Philadelphia, and can do the trade near Tanners, Surplus City, Classic Pistol, or Claytons.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig Sauer 516 Patrol FDE, $1500 OBO or trade
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is my Sig 516 Patrol FDE, which I bought new.

From the Sig website:

     "The SIG516 Patrol FDE in Flat Dark Earth with a matching FDE Cerakote® finish on both the upper and lower receivers and aluminum handguard. As with all SIG516 Patrol rifles, the Flat Dark Earth uses the SIG SAUER innovative short-stroke gas pushrod operating system, which reduces chamber debris and allows the rifle to run cleaner and cooler. 

     This system, along with the SIG SAUER proprietary fully supported extractor enables the SIG516 to be one of the only rifles to pass NATO’s “Over the Beach” test.

     A 16” Nitride treated barrel is chambered in 5.56mm NATO and is surrounded by a free-floating aluminum quad rail forend."

     My rifle has proprietary Sig flip-up iron sights and a full length top rail as well as Magpul furniture including an adjustable buttstock and a SAW style grip. I have a cheapo folding drop vertical grip on it that I had laying around. It will come with 6 magpul Pmags, an aluminum mag ( all are 30 rd mags),  a two point sling, two rotating sling attachment lugs, three rail covers, a cleaning kit, and about 120 rounds with it. The case in the picture DOES NOT come with it unless I need to make up some value; it is a $100 two-gun case and its brand new.
      This rifle was a one of a commemorative run for the Saturn Arch corporation. It came with Saturn Arch's logo laser-engraved into the right side of the receiver. I decided that was too pretty so I had a local plaque shop do a metallic subdued 29th ID decal for me. The decal could easily come off and the residue would be able to be cleaned with rubbing alcohol or goo-b-gone with no harm to the cerakote finish. If I kept it I was going to have the engraving painted over with FDE powdercoating.
     This rifle has so little recoil, its like shooting a 22! Quickest return to target of any semiauto carbine i've ever shot. And it needs so little cleaning after being shot; im told that (and reliability) are because of the piston driven system. The only reason i'm selling or trading it is that I want a 308 battle rifle that I can also hunt with, and I'm just not sure that I need an AR-15.  

   For a sale, I just want to see a valid picture ID. For trade, the same, although I will want to do a search by serial # on your guns before we trade to make they arent stolen.

title: For Sale:  SOLD- 1942 Russian Tula Mosin Nagant M91/30 Round Receiver -7.62x54R w/ Bayonet BRASS fittings
postcontent:
Note: Interested parties must pick up rifle in Dallas, TX. Cash only (no checks, cc, paypal or trades).


This Century International Arms imported WWII rifle is a Tula made Russian M91/30 Mosin Nagant with a great bore. All serial #'s match on the Bolt, Butt Plate, Trigger Guard, & Receiver. Only the bayonet has a different Serial #. This rifle is in excellent condition and appears to have 99% of its finish intact on both metal and wooden surfaces-- with no dings in any of the brass fittings. Scratches and dings are minimal in both wood and metal surfaces. What blemishes are present are no doubt the result of being moved about in a rifle box for the better part of 70 years! It's excellent condition suggests it was probably an unissued surplus rifle as it shows the type of wear that rifles stored in boxes and moved about would have. The brass fittings suggest, in my opinion, a rifle issued to a higher ranking officer-- as most Nagants I've seen (from this time period) are either without fittings or have plain steel fittings. I meticulously removed cosmoline from every nook and cranny on this rifle-- which was laid on thick when I received it. I took this out to the range just once and shoots just as it should-- which is to say that it is extremely accurate shooting the Russian surplus ammo I purchased a case of. I put roughly 30 rounds through it down range and it has a nearly effortless bolt locking action, which is not the case for a lot of mosin nagants I've handled throughout the years. I gave it a final clean out prior to storing it and it's good to go.  I still have a bulk of that ammo available for purchase (about a case and a half) if you're looking to buy quality ammo at a reduced price (look at my other listings for the ammo). Comes with a case, bayonet, a toolkit, the ammo pouch and a tin of cosmoline as pictured.

These are very durable, reliable and accurate rifles. It also looks very impressive with the bayonet extended. The M91/30 rifle was developed after the Germans overran and killed thousands of Soviet soldiers equipped with the M38 carbine which had no provisions for a bayonet. The M91/30 was intended to be issued to all soldiers, replacing not only carbines but rifles as well. The M91/30 was used by many countries following the war, and was a favorite of the Israeli Haganah.

To view a slideshow of all pictures of this rifle copy the following link below and paste it in your browser's address bar:

http://s73.photobucket.com/user/masterpoetaster/slideshow/1943%20CAI%20imported%20Russian%20Izhevsk%20Mosin%20Nagant/1942%20Russian%20Mosin%20Nagant
